04748nam a22005415i 9780226242828DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014044795  a9780226242828  a(DE-B1597)568258  a(OCoLC)1233041573  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aD16b.B876 2015 4aD16b.B876 2015 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a907.2/022231 aBrown, Kate, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDispatches from Dystopia :bHistories of Places Not Yet Forgotten /cKate Brown. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b20 halftones, 7 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Being There -- t2 The Panama Hotel, Japanese America, and the Irrepressible Past -- t3 History (Im)possible in the Chernobyl Zone -- t4 Bodily Secrets -- t5 Sacred Space in a Sullied Garden -- t6 Gridded Lives: Why Kazakhstan and Montana Are Nearly the Same Place -- t7 Returning Home to Rustalgia -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“Why are Kazakhstan and Montana the same place?” asks one chapter of Kate Brown’s surprising and unusual journey into the histories of places on the margins, overlooked or erased. It turns out that a ruined mining town in Kazakhstan and Butte, Montana—America’s largest environmental Superfund site—have much more in common than one would think thanks to similarities in climate, hucksterism, and the perseverance of their few hardy inhabitants. Taking readers to these and other unlikely locales, Dispatches from Dystopia delves into the very human and sometimes very fraught ways we come to understand a particular place, its people, and its history. In Dispatches from Dystopia, Brown wanders the Chernobyl Zone of Alienation, first on the Internet and then in person, to figure out which version—the real or the virtual—is the actual forgery. She also takes us to the basement of a hotel in Seattle to examine the personal possessions left in storage by Japanese-Americans on their way to internment camps in 1942. In Uman, Ukraine, we hide with Brown in a tree in order to witness the annual male-only Rosh Hashanah celebration of Hasidic Jews. In the Russian southern Urals, she speaks with the citizens of the small city of Kyshtym, where invisible radioactive pollutants have mysteriously blighted lives. Finally, Brown returns home to Elgin, Illinois, in the midwestern industrial rust belt to investigate the rise of “rustalgia” and the ways her formative experiences have inspired her obsession with modernist wastelands. Dispatches from Dystopia powerfully and movingly narrates the histories of locales that have been silenced, broken, or contaminated. In telling these previously unknown stories, Brown examines the making and unmaking of place, and the lives of the people who remain in the fragile landscapes that are left behind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDisasters. 0aHazardous geographic environments. 0aHistoriography. 0aTravel. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahistory, dystopia, dystopian, historical, professor, academic, scholarly, learning, textbook, liminal, margins, marginal, mining, butte, montana, kazakhstan, superfund, climate, community, international, chernobyl, alienation, internet, virtual, forgery, fieldwork, internment camps, japanese american, immigrants, conflict, ukraine, language, oppression, racism, locales, hasidic jews, judaism, place, pollution, citizens, radioactive.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97802262